post_text:
Parents, do you know what tomorrow will look like as students begin heading back to campus? Rosewood High School has been posting some great Back-To-School tips!

As our schools' transition to Plan B tomorrow, please make sure your child knows what group they are in and what days they need to be on campus for classes. Reach out to your child's school or teacher if you are unsure when they are expected in person. For more back to school information and resources, head over to the district website.
shared_text:
Rosewood High School
September 3 at 6:10 PM ·

Back to school tip of the day-parents you can download the app for canvas to stay up to date with your students classes as well as their assignments. To get the code please contact one of your child’s teachers.

FYI
Car riders will need to show the attestation form signed by parents to our drop off staff EACH DAY. The form can stay with the parent in the car. Temperatures will be taken at the car before parents drive off.

Bus riders must have this form signed by parents EACH DAY and show it to the bus driver EACH DAY before boarding the bus. Temperatures will be taken when students arrive on campus.

We CANNOT have parents on campus at all to drop off students until 7:00am. Please do not come on campus and park and wait. Drive through the front area only, beginning at 7:00am, no sooner.

Thank you for your patience and understanding. We are all working hard to keep our students and staff safe.

***buses are available to pick up and drop off students for parent convenience***

Visit 2020census.gov to respond today.

All of our schools are officially back in session tomorrow. Our commitment to tasty, nutritious meals is the same regardless of whether the instruction is in the classroom or done remotely at home!

Daily curbside meals will resume tomorrow from 11:30 AM-1:00 PM on all of our campuses except Edgewood Community Developmental School, Wayne Academy, and WEMCHS. For students on campus at WEMCHS and Wayne School of Engineering, meals will continue to be served at school. Students from ECDS, WEMCHS, and Wayne Academy can pick-up a meal at the school nearest them.

With the first three weeks of school being remote instruction, please ensure you have spoken with your child's teacher or school last week about Back to School face-to-face induction meetings. If you haven't, please call the school tomorrow to schedule your meeting.

post_text:
Parents, is your child interested in taking an advanced mathematics course? If they initially did not place into the advanced mathematics course for the 2020-2021 school year, they have the opportunity to request to take the prior grade level EOG or course EOC to determine if they are eligible for advanced mathematics placement!

Administration of the EOG/EOC is voluntary and is only necessary if the student is not already placed in the advanced placement for their grade or course.

Additional information as well as the request form can be found on our district website. All requests must be submitted to the school administrator from August 3, 2020, to August 10, 2020. Testing will be completed from August 10, 2020, to August 14, 2020.

Ayer, la Junta de Educación de WCPS en una decisión dividida 4-2 votó para reabrir las escuelas bajo el Plan C - Instrucción Remota Completa - durante las primeras tres semanas de clases para todas las escuelas, excepto Wayne Early / Middle College High y Wayne School of Engineering. El primer día de clases para todas las escuelas seguirá siendo el mismo.

Esta decisión se tomó para darle al distrito más tiempo para proporcionar capacitación a los maestros, obtener datos precisos de inscripción, preparar rutas de autobús y preparar edificios para los estudiantes que regresan.

Se puede leer las ultimas actualización visitando www.waynecountyschools.org y haciendo clic en Actualizaciones de reapertura escolar 2020-2021.

The registration has closed for our Virtual Learning Program. Unless it is for a special circumstance and approved by the principal, or the district, applications will no longer be accepted.

If your child has been officially registered for the program, the deadline to withdraw has been extended to Friday, August 7. All registered students and families will receive further information about the program, and how to sign up for a WCPS loaner device, class schedules, assigned teachers, grading and testing, state attendance policies, and other information by Monday, August 10th. The email address that was used to register for the program must be correct in order to receive this information.

For more information about the Virtual Learning Program, go to our district website.

post_text:
Wayne County Public School students who were not initially placed into the advanced mathematics course for the 2020-2021 school year, have the opportunity to request to take the prior grade level EOG or course EOC, if they choose to do so, to determine if they are eligible for advanced mathematics placement.

Administration of the EOG/EOC is voluntary and is only necessary if the student is not already placed in the advanced placement for their grade or course.

Our district website has additional information, the necessary request form and Spanish, French, and Creole translations. All requests must be submitted to the school administrator or guidance counselor by August 10, 2020. Testing will be completed from August 10, 2020, to August 14, 2020.

post_text:
Our community is still working hard to ensure no one who needs a meal goes without one!

If you’re in need of food assistance for your child, check out all the locations in our county where free meals are served, many locations serving daily.
shared_text:
The Housing Authority of the City of Goldsboro
July 27 at 10:35 AM ·

#WayneCountyNC Food Heroes👇🏽

Community Soup Kitchen of Goldsboro,Inc. (112 W. Oak Street) serves take-out Monday thru Saturday from 11:00 to 12:00 pm

The Salvation Army of Goldsboro, NC distributes Food boxes Monday through Friday from 8:30 to 4:30. and perishables are distributed daily at 2:30 pm

Rebuilding Broken Places CDC (2105 N William Street) is serving lunch weekdays (must be under 18) from 12:00 pm till 1:30 pm. See flyer below for additional meal sites.

Boys & Girls Clubs of Wayne County (1401 Royall Ave) meals available from 11:30 to 1pm.

Herman Park Center (901 E. Ash St) summer meals available from 11:30 to 12:30pm

Wa Foster Recreation Center (1012 S. John St.) pick up meals from 12:15 to 1:15pm

4354 US 117 Alt, Dudley NC meals sponsored by Three in One Family Center available from 11 to 1pm.

Wayne County Government, North Carolina is conducting free COVID-19 testing at Grantham Middle School on July 21, 2020 and July 23, 2020 from 9 a.m. to 12 p.m.

Testing is open to everyone, regardless of symptoms, and pre-registration is strongly recommended to ensure a testing spot. Testing will be conducted in a drive-thru setting but walk-up visitors, or visitors who did not pre-register, will also be accepted. Bilingual staff will be on-site to assist anyone who needs a translator.
For more info visit https://www.waynegov.com/1025/FREE-Community-Testing

Wayne County Government, North Carolina is conducting free COVID-19 testing at Grantham Middle School on July 21, 2020 and July 23, 2020 from 9 a.m. to 12 p.m.

Testing is open to everyone, regardless of symptoms, and pre-registration is strongly recommended to ensure a testing spot. Testing will be conducted in a drive-thru setting but walk-up visitors, or visitors who did not pre-register, will also be accepted. Bilingual staff will be on-site to assist anyone who needs a translator.

We hosted an awesome professional collaboration recently that welcomed different perspectives and open discussion. We are so grateful to all the committed educators and public education advocates who shared their thoughts and ideas.

Thank you to Freebird McKinney for participating and sharing these great pictures.
shared_text:
Freebird McKinney is at Wayne County Public Schools.
July 15 at 1:40 PM · Goldsboro, NC ·

Thank you, Ken Derksen, for organizing and hosting a morning of collaboration and collective thought provoking “idea mining.” Such an insightful and meaningful conversation with dedicated and committed school leadership in Wayne County Public Schools.

Thank you for the time and the opportunity to learn from you all, particularly, Principals Makita Jenkins, Sheila Wolfe, Wendy Hooks, Catherine Lassiter, Ryan Melson, and Kevin Smith. The NC State Board of Education appreciates your service to @ncpublicschools. #EducatorDiplomats #NCSBELeads

A new, free exhibit is coming to the Wayne County Museum! “The Whole Hog: A History of Eastern NC Barbecue" will be open from 10am-6pm tomorrow.

Parents, if you’re looking for a fun and educational day trip day, check out this new exhibit and learn more about legendary pit-masters, their techniques and their restaurants.
shared_text:
Wayne County Museum
July 3 at 11:33 AM ·

Tomorrow is the opening of our new exhibit, "The Whole Hog: A History of Eastern NC Barbecue". We will be open from 10am-6pm tomorrow. Come learn more about legendary pit-masters, their techniques and their restaurants. We will have some fascinating artifacts from BBQ's local history and information on restaurants from both the past and the present.
This exhibit is free and will run until October 24th. Masks will be required to enter the museum and social distancing measures will be in place. Message us or call 919-734-5023 for more information. We look forward to seeing you and thank you for your support! 🐖❤️

We anticipate that our T-Birds will have lots of real graduations in their futures! Fly, T-Birds, fly!!!!

👏 We are excited to announce our Teacher of the Week recipients, join us in congratulating them!

Susan Hartman is a first-grade teacher 👩‍🏫 at Northeast Elementary, Wayne County Public Schools.

The shift to remote learning sent Susan on an 💻 #edtech journey where not only she had to learn new skills 💡 but also had to teach those skills to parents and students.

While finding the right balance ⚖️ between online learning and hands-on activities was a challenge in the beginning, Susan says watching her students blossom 🌺 and grow 🌱 has been her biggest success.

We appreciate all you do, Susan.

Need some magical fun this summer? Check out our local, public library!

For more information, or to register for this year's Summer Reading Program with Wayne County Public Library, please call your local library or email them at WCPLSummerReadingProgram@gmail.com, or go to http://www.wcpl.org/kids/
shared_text:
Wayne County Public Library
May 22 at 6:01 PM ·

The Wayne County Public Library takes an active role in helping Wayne County’s youth thrive during the summer through our annual Summer Reading Program. Beginning the week of June 22, we will be airing programs most weekdays for 7 weeks, ending these special programs on August 6. Our theme this year is “Imagine Your Story,” and we will hear many folktales, myths, legends, and old stories told in new and exciting ways.

When you register, you’ll receive a Summer Adventure Packet, which will include craft supplies and activities for your family to use to follow along with us at home and to have your own fun whenever you please. To ensure you receive your Summer Adventure Packet before our programs begin, register before June 5.

We are so thrilled to spend another summer with you, and are looking forward to imagining and writing the next part of our story together.

For more information, or to register for this year's Summer Reading Program, please call your local library or email us at WCPLSummerReadingProgram@gmail.com, or go to http://www.wcpl.org/kids/

Independientemente de los ingresos, NC Department of Health and Human Services proporciona suplementos monetarios a las familias que califican para los estudiantes que estudien en cualquier escuela de WCPS que ofrezca comidas sin costo, o para los estudiantes que son elegibles en base a solicitudes de comidas gratis o de precio reducido.

Este programa ayudar a las familias a comprar alimentos para sus hijos mientras los edificios escolares están cerrados. A las familias que califiquen y que ya reciben asistencia alimentaria y nutricional del gobierno se les agregarán fondos adicionales a sus tarjetas EBT.

NCDHHS está enviando tarjetas P-EBT por correo a todas las familias calificadas que actualmente no reciben asistencia alimentaria y nutricional del gobierno. Puede encontrar más información en el sito web.

This program will help families purchase food for their children while school buildings are closed. Qualifying families who already receive government food and nutrition assistance will have additional funds added to their EBT cards.

NCDHHS is mailing P-EBT cards to all qualifying families not currently receiving government food and nutrition assistance. For more information visit the website below.

This week, we learned that 20 of our schools have earned the Purple Star Award! NC Public Schools (NCDPI) awards this to schools for their demonstrated military-friendly practices and a commitment to military students and families.

We have worked to maintain a strong relationship with Seymour Johnson Air Force Base and to ensure that our schools have a network of supports to help address the unique challenges military-connected families face.

The WCPS schools which received the Purple Star Award include:
Charles B. Aycock High, Eastern Wayne Elementary, Eastern Wayne High, Eastern Wayne Middle, Fremont Stars Elementary, Greenwood Middle, Grantham Elementary, Grantham Middle, Meadow Lane Elementary, Northeast Elementary, Northwest Elementary, Norwayne Middle, Rosewood Elementary, Rosewood Middle, Rosewood High, Spring Creek Elementary, Spring Creek Middle, Spring Creek High, Tommy's Road Elementary, and Wayne School of Engineering.

https://www.waynecountyschools.org/protected/ArticleView.aspx?iid=5IPIBY&dasi=3AI2

post_text:
Remote learning has taken on a new look for some of our students!

Check out Jahyra picking up a sewing machine from Spring Creek High and Tatiyana using a school sewing machine at home. "Mostly I have fixed clothes for my family like I fixed my little brother's sleeping bag and his pants and shirts," said Tatiyana. "I’m also turning a dress into a cardigan for my mom. Most recent though, I have been working on a homemade facemask."

Sewing machines are now being checked out for students taking high school Family Consumer Science Apparel II courses. The courses are part of the district's Career & Technical Education program. Most recent though, I have been working on a homemade facemask."

Do you or your family lack reliable Internet at home for remote learning? Our “Park & Learn” initiative with United Way of Wayne County, North Carolina can help!

Park & Learn allows families to take advantage of identified parking areas around Wayne County that have free and publicly accessible WiFi for students to use to complete online homework and activities.

Families who cannot access a copy of the list can call 919-735-3591 to help find a Park & Learn location nearest them.

En los últimos dos días, varios anuncios importantes han salido de Raleigh con respecto a la educación pública. Ayer, la Junta de Educación del Estado aprobó actualizaciones de póliza con respecto a las calificaciones finales para los estudiantes K-11.

Esta tarde, el gobernador de Carolina del Norte, Cooper, anunció que el aprendizaje remoto continuaría durante el resto del año académico. Esto significa que mientras los edificios permanecerán cerrados, la enseñanza y el aprendizaje continuarán.

Agradecemos a todas nuestras familias que trabajan con sus hijos y los ayudan a mantenerse conectados con sus aulas virtuales y el aprendizaje remoto y/o mantenerse al día con sus recursos de aprendizaje impresos durante este tiempo.

Por favor vaya a nuestro sito web para la actualización completa y recursos adicionales de NCDPI.

Over the past two days, several major announcements have come out of Raleigh regarding public education. Yesterday, the State Board of Education approved policy updates regarding final grades for students K -11.

This afternoon, North Carolina Governor Cooper announced that remote learning would continue for the remainder of the academic year. This means that while buildings will remain closed, teaching and learning will continue.

We thank all of our families who are working with their children and helping them stay connected to their virtual classrooms and remote learning and/or keeping up with their printed learning resources during this time.

Please see our website for a complete update and additional resources from NCDPI.

#OurNCSchoolHeros are doing amazing things every day! Patricia Velasco, a
Goldsboro High science teacher, made masks over Spring Break to help protect our School Nutrition staff while they work to make meals for students.

This morning, the staff at CarverHeights_ES received their masks and were wearing them as they prepped food for the meal pick-up site at their school. Thank you, Patricia, for your generous contribution to our student feeding efforts. We want to say a big thank you to our school nutrition staff as well who have been working for weeks to serve our students. #OurNCSchoolHeros are too many to count here at WCPS!

#OurNCSchoolHeros have been doing amazing work in our community all week! All 10 of our meal pick-up sites are active and distributing thousands of meals.

We couldn’t be more grateful to our partners through this! A big thanks goes out The Salvation Army of Goldsboro, NC for organizing the large feeding effort for our students this week.
shared_text:
The Salvation Army of Goldsboro, NC
April 16 at 10:27 PM ·

More meals served today! All 10 Wayne County Public Schools locations. We are averaging 3,000 meals PER DAY!! Again with churches, volunteers, local small business restaurants, companies & community members volunteering their time to be sure our local kids have a meal today! There were meals left over so we hit the streets in our Mobile Disaster Canteen with volunteers willing to serve. We fed children at Day Circle, Alpha Arms, local hotels, & a few more places. So many kids smiling & saying things like "the spaghetti is delicious!" & "I want hot dogs & applesauce!" & "thank you!". Parents coming out saying "I haven't been able to get my kids to the schools this week for meals, thank you for coming out here!" THAT IS WHAT OUR COMMUNITY IS DOING T-O-G-E-T-H-E-R!!! Doing the MOST Good!!
Way to go Wayne County!! 1 more day!!
#WayneCountyUnited

post_text: Wayne Community College has now joined our list of Park & Learn sites! Check out how to get WiFi on their campus below.
shared_text:
Wayne CC News & Views
April 17 at 1:32 AM ·

If you miss learning at WCC, we have a change that can get you back on campus, just not back into the classroom.
Wireless coverage has been boosted on campus to create drive-up Wi-Fi hotspots. They are
1) the parking lot between the Wayne Learning Center and the digital marquee at the front of the campus,
2) the parking lot adjacent to the new construction, and
3) the parking lot in front of the Spruce building (across from the tennis courts) at the back of the campus.
United Way of Wayne County has created a list of “Park and Learn” open Wi-Fi sites around Wayne County (www.unitedwayne.org/). For assistance with finding the site nearest you, call 919-735-3591.
The NC Department of Information Technology provides lists of public Wi-Fi access locations and free or affordable service offerings from vendors across the state (www.ncbroadband.gov/covid19broadband/). It includes an interactive map to help locate free Wi-Fi.
Remember to follow the rules of social distancing when working at public Wi-Fi access locations.
#COVID19NC #WCCGettingThroughThis #TheCollegeInTheCommunity

¡Las vacaciones de primavera comienzan mañana y se extenderán hasta el próximo viernes 17 de abril! Eso significa que tenemos una nueva actualización muy importante en nuestro sitio web para nuestros padres, estudiantes y personal.

Aquí están los aspectos más destacados:
1) ¡Estamos muy agradecidos por todo el trabajo duro que todos han estado haciendo en estas últimas semanas! Hemos visto cosas increíbles sucediendo en todo el distrito últimamente y es gracias a ustedes, nuestros increíbles padres, estudiantes y personal.

2) Todos los sitios de distribución de comidas WCPS están cerrados este viernes. La próxima semana, el Salvation Army distribuirá comidas en los diez sitios, lunes, martes, miércoles, jueves y viernes de 11:30 a.m. a 1 p.m.

3) ¡Todos le deseamos unas vacaciones de primavera seguras y agradables!

Lea la actualización completa en nuestro sitio web

Spring Break begins tomorrow, and will run through next Friday, April 17! That means we've got a new, very important update on our website for our parents, students, and staff.

Here are the highlights:
1) We are so thankful for all the hardwork everyone has been putting in these past few weeks! We've seen amazing things happening all over the distrcit lately and it's because of you, our awesome parents, students, and staff.

2) All WCPS meal distribution sites are closed this Friday. Next week, the Salvation Army will be distributing meals at all ten sites, Monday, Tuesday, Wednesday, Thursday and Friday from 11:30 AM until 1 PM!

3) We are all wishing you a safe and enjoyable Spring Break!

Read the complete update on our website.

The Salvation Army of Goldsboro, NC
April 7 at 9:52 PM ·

So exciting!!! We are so thankful for the MANY volunteers, leaders & community partners making this happen for our local schools!!

Reminder: Spring Break is April 10-April 17 for all schools.
This Thursday, April 9, all ten meal distribution sites will provide meals for both Thursday and Friday for those students who need this service. All sites will be closed on Friday.

Next week, The Salvation Army will be stepping in to distribute meals at all ten sites, Monday, Tuesday, Wednesday, Thursday and Friday from 11:30 AM until 1 PM. Together with their support, Wayne County Public Schools can ensure there is no gap in service while we give our hard-working school nutrition workers a much-needed break.

shared_text:
UNITEDWAYNE.ORG
WiFi Sponsored | uw-of-wayne-county

United Way of Wayne County, North Carolina
April 6 at 4:11 PM ·

Thanks to you, our students have found a signal!

Wayne County #parkadnddlearn sites are ready for our students. Flyers will be distributed at Wayne County Public Schools feeding sites this week. Please help us share this information.

To remain in compliance with Governor Cooper’s Stay at Home Order, families and students taking advantage of “Park & Learn” opportunities must stay in their vehicle while parked and return home once they are completed. At no time, should any student or family member leave their vehicle to congregate with others who are also visiting the public wifi sites. The WiFi signal strength will vary from site to site. We encourage you to find a site that works best for your child and the mobile learning device they are using. UWWC and Wayne County Public Schools thanks all of the WiFi Sponsors who have made this "Park & Learn" initiative possible for students to take part in online remote learning!

https://www.unitedwayne.org/superheroes

Do you or your family lack reliable Internet at home? This week, we launched a “Park & Learn” initiative with United Way of Wayne County, North Carolina!

This allows families to take advantage of identified parking areas around Wayne County which have free and publicly accessible WiFi for students to use to complete online homework and activities.

Families who cannot access a copy of the list can call 919-735-3591 to help find a Park & Learn location nearest them.

City Government of Goldsboro, NC
April 1 at 10:51 AM ·

The City of Goldsboro will light its Holly Street Water Tower during the COVID-19 State of Emergency as a symbol of hope for all and a sign of support for our heroes on the front lines of the battle against this deadly disease.

“We are thankful for the efforts of everyone to slow the spread of COVID-19 and mitigate its impact to the health, welfare, and well-being of our residents and visitors,” said Goldsboro City Manager Tim Salmon. “ I am proud of the professionalism our City employees have displayed and encourage all to seek COVID-19 best practices for what they do and use them to potentially save lives.”

Actualización: Las vacaciones de primavera se llevarán como programado, del 10 de abril al 17 de abril. Esto les dará a todos nuestros estudiantes, padres y personal un descanso necesario después de participar en este nuevo estilo de enseñanza y aprendizaje que se ha implementado durante El cierre de las escuelas estatal.

Durante las vacaciones de primavera, el distrito no distribuirá comidas para darles a todos nuestros trabajadores de la cafetería un descanso necesario. Estamos trabajando con las agencias locales y del condado para garantizar que existan programas de comidas comunitarias, para que no haya una brecha en el servicio para los estudiantes durante el receso.

Se proporcionará más información una vez que se finalicen los detalles. Como siempre, estas y otras actualizaciones están disponibles en el sitio web del distrito, www.waynecountyschools.org.

UPDATE: Spring Break will be held as scheduled, April 10 through April 17 to give all of our students, parents, and staff a needed break after being thrown into this new style of remote teaching and learning that has been put in place during the statewide school closure.

During Spring Break, we will not be distributing meals in order to give all of our hard working cafeteria workers a needed break too. We are working with the county and local agencies to ensure there are community meal programs in place, so that there is no gap in service for students over the break.

More information will be provided once details are finalized. As always, these and other updates are available on the district website, www.waynecountyschools.org.

post_text: Today the NC Board of Education approved special rules to help seniors graduate on time. WCPS counselors will be reaching out to seniors next week to share more information.
shared_text:
CONTENT.GOVDELIVERY.COM
State Board of Education Approves Steps to Cope with COVID-19 Fallout

NC Public Schools
March 27 at 5:41 PM ·

The State Board of Education took steps on three different fronts today to support schools across North Carolina coping with the fallout of the COVID-19 pandemic.

- The board approved a grading policy to enable high school seniors to graduate on time. The board also approved guidance for districts and schools to encourage remote teaching and learning while also recognizing the challenges that many students and families face without digital access.

-In response to Gov. Roy Cooper’s executive action earlier this week to provide $50 million in COVID-19 related support to districts and schools, the board approved a formula for allocating those funds based on a combination of student enrollment and poverty levels.

-The Board also approved an emergency paid-leave policy for public school employees for the month of April that addresses COVID-19 and related issues.

post_text:
Today, approximately 1,800 meals were given out across the ten sites! With such a large response, we will be adding a new site at Brogden Middle, which will open on Thursday. Our Nutrition Department will also be bringing in additional cafeteria staff to assist at the sites.

Again, we appreciate all of the offers from staff and community members to volunteer their assistance with meal distributions. However, we are only allowing school nutrition staff to operate at the sites to limit the number of individuals at these sites during these times.

Dr. Michael Dunsmore, superintendent, states, “I am awed by the staff who helped meet the overwhelming response from families who took advantage of the meal distribution events today, I cannot be more proud of our School Nutrition Department and all of the cafeteria workers who helped make WCPS among the first school districts in North Carolina to offer this level of service during this closure.”
text:
Today, approximately 1,800 meals were given out across the ten sites! With such a large response, we will be adding a new site at Brogden Middle, which will open on Thursday. Our Nutrition Department will also be bringing in additional cafeteria staff to assist at the sites.

Again, we appreciate all of the offers from staff and community members to volunteer their assistance with meal distributions. However, we are only allowing school nutrition staff to operate at the sites to limit the number of individuals at these sites during these times.

Dr. Michael Dunsmore, superintendent, states, “I am awed by the staff who helped meet the overwhelming response from families who took advantage of the meal distribution events today, I cannot be more proud of our School Nutrition Department and all of the cafeteria workers who helped make WCPS among the first school districts in North Carolina to offer this level of service during this closure.”

post_text:
We are blown away by the amazing outpouring of support for our schools by both our staff and our community. We appreciate every offer and message we have seen in the past couple of days! Unfortunately, federal guidelines prohibit us from taking outside food, so if you'd like to drop off food and help the community during this time of need, we would like to encourage you to please donate to The Salvation Army of Goldsboro, NC

Thank you for all the support as we continue to work through the many challenges involved in coordinating the most effective response to this public health emergency.

Regardless of the type of sickness, here are some steps you should take if your child is sick.

-Keep your child at home if they vomiting, having diarrhea, or running a fever of 100 degrees. Remember to come back to school a full 24 hours must pass after the symptoms have stopped.

-Do not share dishes, drinking glasses, cups, eating utensils, towels, or bedding with people who are sick in the home.

-Clean AND disinfect frequently touched surfaces daily. This includes tables, doorknobs, light switches, countertops, handles, desks, phones, keyboards, toilets, faucets, and sinks.

Make sure your child stays home except to get medical care. We hope you will follow the best practices for helping prevent the spread of germs and sickness in our schools.
Learn More: https://www.waynecountyschools.org/COVID-19.aspx

Regardless of the type of sickness, here are some steps we can all take to better protect ourselves!

-Washing hands with soap and water, often! When washing, use soap and water for at least 20 seconds, especially after you have been in a public place.

-Avoid touching your eyes, nose, and mouth with unwashed hands.

-Always cough into your elbow or sleeve and avoid touching your eyes, mouth, or eyes.

-Avoid close contact with people who are sick. This is especially important for people who are at higher risk of getting very sick.

Make sure your child stays home except to get medical care. We hope you will follow the best practices for helping prevent the spread of germs and sickness in our schools.
Learn More: https://www.waynecountyschools.org/COVID-19.aspx

Wayne County Museum
March 4 at 12:30 PM ·

Less than TWO WEEKS away! Come join us at the museum on Saturday, March 14th from 1pm until 2:30pm for our Fairytale Festival: The World is Our Stage event! This program is for children in kindergarten, first and second grade. A group of first grade students from Northwest Elementary School, led by their teacher Crystal Hodges, will participate in an interactive reader's theater experience with a performance of 'The Three Little Pigs'. After the performance, the audience will get to explore their problem solving skills by using a variety of fairytale STEM kits. This fun and educational event is free! Come spend your Saturday downtown with the Wayne County Museum!

post_text:
Due to below freezing temperatures and the threat of icy conditions expected to impact bridges and roadways for much of the morning, the following actions are being taken:

All schools will be CLOSED for both students and staff tomorrow, Friday, February 21.
All athletic events and practices have been canceled for Friday.
All campuses will remain closed to students, faculty, and the general public this weekend.

post_text:
Due to the threat of inclement weather forecast for our area beginning as early as tomorrow afternoon, the following actions are being taken for Thursday, February 20:

• All schools on the Traditional Academic Calendar along with Goldsboro High School will dismiss three (3) hours early
• All after school programs are canceled for Thursday afternoon
• Wayne Early/Middle College High School and the Wayne School of Engineering will be CLOSED to students and it will be an Optional Workday for staff.
